    {
        "content": "<p><span aria-label=\"memo\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f4dd\" role=\"img\" title=\"memo\">:memo:</span> bjorn3 submitted <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/13815#pullrequestreview-4638861002\">PR review</a>.</p>",
        "id": 608517213,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1783363897
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span aria-label=\"speech balloon\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f4ac\" role=\"img\" title=\"speech balloon\">:speech_balloon:</span> bjorn3 created <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/13815#discussion_r3531344745\">PR review comment</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>You can select between thumb and arm on a per-function basis in LLVM and Rust, so changing the target triple is not the only way of choosing thumb mode. <code>#[instruction_set(arm::t32)]</code> lowers to what is effectively <code>#[target_feature(enable = \"thumb-mode\")]</code> in the LLVM backend of rustc. And a couple of rustc targets also use <code>target_features: \"+thumb-mode\"</code> in the target spec.</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 608517215,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1783363898
    }
]